,Recommended,218510,8737802,"Posted: 17 January, 2014",all,timesovgrace,"""Planets Under Attack"" is a strategy gem: very simple concept, yet has just enough depth to the gameplay to make it not just addicting but weirdly satisfying, especially after playing tug of war with the AI over a planet for what seems like forever and finally ripping it from their hands at the same time you attack their last planet.A quick summary of the gameplay: you start with usually one planet in one of multiple gametypes, including a deathmatch type, king of the hill type, and a gametype where you vie for control of specific planets ( the first to control all the marked planets wins, regardless of how many planets the other players have). You click on another planet and hold the mouse button to determine how many ships you want to send; neutral planets/your own planets dont cost any money to invade, but enemy planets do--at least for the human race, the only race i've played as so far, but i've read that the robots play differently--and you go from there, upgrading your planets to increase taxes and building up your defenses by transferring ships to increase the population. Again, on the surface, simple, but a game can quickly dissolve into chaos requiring quick thinking and quicker clicking to turn the tide.Definitely recommended if you get a coupon, but for $10, its a great strategy time killer that also has a fun multiplayer. Check it out."
