76561198032573928,Recommended,218510,28813812,"Posted: 29 December, 2016",all,Murgen,"I'm conflicted about giving this an up vote because while I did enjoy it I feel the difficulty level is so high that most gamers will quickly quit out of frustration.It's a micro-managing strategy game in which you control planets that give you money and ships over time. The money can be spent on upgrades, attacks, or hoarded for a combat buff. The ships are sent out in streams to conquer enemy planets and defend your own.This genre of game is not new, and variants of it can be found for free on sites like Kongregate. But this game has much better graphics and sound/music compared to the free versions.There are various tech upgrades that you can earn and equip in a limited number of slots. There are different game types to keep things fresh such as Elimination (kill everyone) and King of the Hill (control a certain planet for a set period of time).There are different kinds of planets and opponents to fight as well. For example, one planet is an ""infested"" planet which is covered with alien eggs. This planet will remain neutral while a timer counts down. When the timer reaches zero the eggs hatch and the previously neutral planet suddenly becomes a major threat. The player will have to weigh the pros and cons of destroying the infested planets before pursuing the main objective, or hoping to rush to victory before the eggs hatch and the situation becomes untenable.The story is about an entrepreneur who goes looking for riches in an uncharted area of space while being hounded by intergalactic debt collectors. It was mildly entertaining but the ending left a lot of loose ends.Multiplayer seems mostly dead, so I played only single player.The controls are simple, actually a little too simple since there is no pause button I could find. Things get hectic very fast in this game with streams of hundreds of ships criss-crossing the map at any given time. A delay of even a few seconds in terms of not attacking or upgrading can spell defeat for the player. The AI is quick to notice any opening in your defenses and pounce.I went into this game thinking it would be casual entertainment that wouldn't make me think. Wrong!It starts out easy enough with some generous tutorial missions. After that the difficulty level starts ramping up exponentionally. By mission 10 I figure most casual gamers have been blown away. By mission 16 I figure all but the most die-hard strategists have been wiped out. I'm a glutton for punishment though, and I like a good challenge, so I toughed it out and beat all 30 missions of the single player campaign. Even the Easy difficulty level was ludicrously difficult. You have been warned!If you're a casual gamer looking for an easy game, look elsewhere. If you're a hardcore strategist who isn't afraid of fast-paced micro-managing this game might be for you."
